      "conditioning_notes": "`<CHAR_A>`'s love of seeing the pattern first and fear of being wrong in public drive the whole arc — they know the wrong section was prepped before anyone announces it, they don't panic, and they redirect rather than retreat. In the arena, where everyone watches, being wrong publicly is the worst outcome; `<CHAR_A>` routes around it by giving the floor to `<CHAR_B>`. The mentor_student dynamic surfaces not in instruction but in permission — `<CHAR_A>` never says \"I believe in you\"; they just step back. `<CHAR_B>`'s love of feeling it all the way is the actual asset here: they can say \"we got it wrong\" with honesty the room responds to because they mean it completely. `<CHAR_B>`'s fear of being too much is what makes the mentor_release beat (\"that's kind of the nicest thing you've ever said\") land quietly instead of loudly. `<CHAR_C>`, also a 📡 Signal, occupies the external-evaluator position — a second pattern-spotter means any slip gets noticed twice, which raises the cost of the mistake without raising the volume. The arena location shapes posture throughout: characters speak in shorter bursts, nothing is private, and even a quiet exchange carries the weight of being visible. The falling arc starts at 3 (everyone is watching, something is wrong) and steps down to 1 (the room shifted, and the student felt it) — tension doesn't crash, it exhales."
